{"blockStates":[{"name":"Quantum Harmonic Oscillator Dynamics","uid":"Sticker #17296c8d695","x":6,"y":5,"width":329,"height":442,"marginX":15,"marginY":15,"userText":"The Schrödinger equation is one of the most important equations in quantum mechanics:\n\n<pre>i&hbar;&part;|&Psi;&rang;/&part;t=Ĥ|&Psi;&rang;</pre>\n\n<p>where &hbar; is the Planck constant, &Psi; is the wave function, Ĥ is the Hamiltonian operator, and t is time. In a one-dimensional position basis, the Schrödinger equation can be written as:\n\n<pre>i&hbar;&part;&Psi;(x,t)/&part;t=[-&hbar;<sup>2</sup>&nabla;<sup>2</sup>/(2m)+V(x,t)]&Psi;(x,t)</pre>\n\n<p>where m is the mass of the particle and V(x, t) is the potential energy function (in the most generic case, it may also be time-varying).\n\n<p>This page shows the motion of a probability density function of a quantum harmonic oscillator in 1D. The system is initially at the ground state with an initial momentum. As you can see, the behavior of a quantum harmonic oscillator resembles that of a classical one to some extent. ","decimals":3,"color":"#808080","textColor":"#ffffff","useHtml":true,"keepResult":false},{"name":"x0","uid":"Slider #1729939a127","x":348,"y":83,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":-10,"maximum":10,"steps":20,"value":-10,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":2},{"name":"Series Block","uid":"Series Block #1729939b60f","x":478,"y":131,"width":60,"height":100,"start":-10,"increment":0.2,"count":100},{"name":"dx","uid":"Slider #172993aa70d","x":347,"y":154,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":0.1,"maximum":0.2,"steps":10,"value":0.2,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":2},{"name":"nx","uid":"Slider #172993b290d","x":347,"y":226,"width":100,"height":60,"minimum":50,"maximum":200,"steps":15,"value":100,"source":true,"snapToTick":true,"valuePrecision":3},{"uid":"Univariate Function Block #1729945f0c7","variableName":"x","expression":"k*x*x/2","x":587,"y":152,"width":127,"height":72},{"name":"Global Variable Block","key"